;t have a dirt floor!!&quot; reply mkesper 1 hour ago | root | parent | prev | next [–] Workers maybe? reply pcthrowaway 1 hour ago | root | parent | next [–] Well fair, but the above commenter seemed to be suggesting there may be people who couldn&#x27;t afford better internet packages, and my assumption was that workers would get access to the internet as part of their employment, but perhaps I&#x27;m assuming wrong. reply billfor 1 hour ago | prev | next [–] Does the SNI tunnel trick (changing the SNI to match the AP) not work on cruise ships? reply evadne 41 minutes ago | prev | next [–] all this for under 10mbps? reply jl6 1 hour ago | prev | next [–] I’m not going to cry hard about stealing from one of the scummiest industries on the planet, and a good hack is a good hack, but man, what a wasted opportunity to disconnect! I guess OP is a kid and gets the FOMO itch from being offline. I feel we as a society are not good at helping people grow out of that. reply sergiotapia 1 hour ago | prev | next [–] With the picture + your name, Princess Cruises will find your booking and probably bill and ban you from their cruiseline? reply jeffbee 2 hours ago | prev | next [–] I would never take a cruise but in other places with paid wifi that I did not want to pay for, IP-over-DNS tunneling worked well. reply OutOfHere 1 hour ago | parent | next [–] Which services or apps do you advise for it? reply EvanAnderson 1 hour ago | root | parent | next [–] Iodine is the go-to for IP-over-DNS tunneling: https:&#x2F;&#x2F;github.com&#x2F;yarrick&#x2F;iodine Back in the Before Times when my wireless telephone didn&#x27;t support tethering &#x2F; hotspot iodine was very handy, albeit excruciatingly slow. Very rarely did I find a network I couldn&#x27;t tunnel out of. Virtually nobody thinks about DNS exfil. (Did a gig one time where we did live-off-the-land exfil of base64 encoded data using CERTUTIL, CMD, PING, and tcpdump running on an off-site DNS server.) reply haunter 2 hours ago | prev | next [–] I&#x27;ve never been to a cruise but want to go one day reply LtWorf 1 hour ago | parent | next [–] It&#x27;s quite boring to be honest. I think it can be good if you have small kids. reply pcthrowaway 1 hour ago | root | parent | next [–] I&#x27;d be interested in a hacker cruise. A boat with 100 hackers on board is in the middle of the ocean when the nav system gains self-awareness and decides not to return to land. The boat is equipped with satellite communication devices, but passenger internet access is off. Only 40 days of rations. Will they be able to hack their way back to shore before they run out of red bull? Or will they turn to a life of piracy instead? reply Jonovono 1 hour ago | root | parent | prev | next [–] Hmm, seeing someone fall&#x2F;jump overboard and then subsequently getting interrogated by the fbi upon docking was anything but boring, reply jiveturkey 1 hour ago | prev | next [–] Besides the fairly well trod hack nature of the post, and my admiration for such hacker nature of it, this describes theft of service. I have mixed feelings, but I wouldn&#x27;t be upset if the title were editorialized to &quot;stealing $170&quot;. reply dale_huevo 2 hours ago | prev | next [–] One of the fringe benefits of going on a cruise is that you can disconnect from the Internet for a week. Hit up the bar, make love to your wife, gamble a bit. All without your phone constantly buzzing in your pocket. If you go on a cruise to immediately open your laptop it seems like a waste of time and money. reply unsnap_biceps 2 hours ago | parent | next [–] The author is &quot;a high school student and aspiring software developer&quot; and I know at their age, being disconnected wasn&#x27;t a benefit :) reply c22 2 hours ago | parent | prev | next [–] What if you&#x27;re a teenager, traveling with your family, and the internet is your lifeblood ? You can&#x27;t gamble or go to the bar and you have no wife, so this sort of activity is respectable. reply duxup 2 hours ago | root | parent | next [–] Some of my best experiences as a teen were those that took me out of whatever bubbles I was in at the time. Vacations are a great time for that. reply bestouff 2 hours ago | root | parent | prev | next [–] Then that&#x27;s a sad story. reply humanperhaps 1 hour ago | root | parent | prev | next [–] To be fair, I was trying to be humorous with that phrasing. reply BeetleB 1 hour ago | parent | prev | next [–] &gt; All without your phone constantly buzzing in your pocket Actually, the benefit is not having her phone not constantly buzzing. reply lainzhow 2 hours ago | parent | prev | next [–] If I got it right, it was a high schooler that posted. So I guess that&#x27;s not an option reply wonger_ 2 hours ago | parent | prev | next [–] Some people use cruises as a productive work retreat: https:&#x2F;&#x2F;tynan.com&#x2F;cruisework&#x2F; But yeah, it&#x27;s nice to be disconnected on vacation. reply lagadu 2 hours ago | parent | prev | next [–] I hate to sound preachy so I apologize if I&#x27;m coming off like that but if someone&#x27;s relationship with the internet is so bad that being put in a situation where being forced to stay off it is seen as a positive, perhaps the whole relationship should be taken a hard look at? reply asadm 2 hours ago | parent | prev | next [–] Unless you LOVE your work and just want a change of scene while doing what you love. reply jonas21 2 hours ago | root | parent | next [–] Then don&#x27;t go on a cruise. There are plenty of places with great scenery AND great connectivity. But a cruise ship is not one of them. reply duxup 2 hours ago | root | parent | prev | next [–] Just seems like a lot of expense that by working you&#x27;re decreasing the value. Also depends on who you&#x27;re traveling with &#x2F; anyone. I&#x27;ve been on trips with the &quot;I have to work&quot; folks, it&#x27;s a pain, they&#x27;re not really &quot;there&quot; you end up trying to schedule around them. Then they just show up unaware &#x2F; uninvolved in whatever is going on. reply asadm 2 hours ago | root | parent | next [–] i think you needed to set expectations. on every trip, i reach a point where i don&#x27;t have any social-interaction points and so i go back to my cave and code. reply duxup 2 hours ago | root | parent | next [–] Oh I have, I just don&#x27;t go with the &quot;I have to work&quot; people, or everyone is on the same page and it&#x27;s just not a thing. reply kennethrc 2 hours ago | root | parent | prev | next [–] ... and even if you&#x27;re just on vacation it&#x27;s not like you&#x27;re doing nothing else but being online, OP ... reply tossandthrow 2 hours ago | parent | prev | next [–] Unless you are on a cruise to work remotely and flee soaring rental prices. reply LtWorf 34 minutes ago | root | parent | next [–] There is no way that a cruise is cheaper. reply happyopossum 1 hour ago | prev | next [–] Oh look - I’m smart and made this theft easy, so the company I’m stealing from deserves it. Yay me! Seriously people, I know that figuring these things out is part of the hacker ethos, but this is still theft of services no matter how you try and justify it. reply baq 17 minutes ago | parent | next [–] This horse is pulp and has been for a long while now but theft of services is not a thing, it’s a breach of contract. reply archagon 4 minutes ago | parent | prev | next [–] Some of the earliest hackers were phone phreakers, and this is essentially a victimless &quot;crime.&quot; (Cost of maritime internet for a cruise line is probably a rounding error in their budget.) reply nopelynopington 2 hours ago | prev [11 more] [flagged] wlll 2 hours ago | parent | next [–] If I earned ~50 million dollars per year then I think I&#x27;d just pay for Internet. Maybe .1% was a bad choice, should we only post articles that are relevant to people on a global average yearly wage of ~$12,000? How are we defining relevant? People earning $2000&#x2F;year might be &#x2F;interested&#x2F; in a thing, but not able to afford it (eg. a Mac computer or a large hadron collider), where do we draw the line? reply JumpCrisscross 2 hours ago | parent | prev | next [–] &gt; This is .1% problems Cruises are a stereotypically mass-market vacation. In most cases they’re cheaper than a hotel. reply Scarblac 2 hours ago | root | parent | next [–] But still, Google says there&#x27;s about 30 million cruise passengers per year, or less than 0.4% of the world. Close. reply JumpCrisscross 2 hours ago | root | parent | next [–] &gt; Google says there&#x27;s about 30 million cruise passengers per year, or less than 0.4% of the world. Close. By the same math owning a pet tortoise is something of a 0.1% game. reply nopelynopington 1 hour ago | root | parent | prev | next [–] Exactly. And then add to that people that just happen to bring an openWRT router on a cruise with them reply BeetleB 1 hour ago | root | parent | prev | next [–] &gt; In most cases they’re cheaper than a hotel. Eh, depends on the package. I went on a 7 day cruise. Definitely not cheaper than a hotel, given that you are paying per person . So if you have 2 kids, you&#x27;d pay roughly $850&#x2F;day. reply ceejayoz 2 hours ago | parent | prev | next [–] That doesn&#x27;t make it non-interesting. reply humanperhaps 2 hours ago | parent | prev [–] Just want to clarify that my intent was not to say that internet is essential. However, I do need internet access for my job and in general, it&#x27;s nice to be able to keep in touch with friends. reply nopelynopington 1 hour ago | root | parent [–] If you need to still be accessible to your job while on a cruise there&#x27;s something wrong somewhere. I mean I guess said job must pay well, but still reply humanperhaps 1 hour ago | root | parent [–] My job is mostly just working on open source software, which I enjoy and would be doing anyway. I actually haven&#x27;t worked on it yet on the cruise, but thought it would be nice to sit by a window and